Candy Race

by: Ella Demarest

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I decided to make this game because I wanted to do something with a scrolling background, and I thought a racing game would be fun to make. I also decided to make it candy themed so I could add in colorful drawings I made to make the game look better, instead of just rectangles. I also thought that I could use what I learned from League Invaders to help me make this game, so I would understand what I was doing more.

2. What I Learned

I got feedback from my teacher that I should make the game harder as the game goes on, and I learned that changing the difficulty of a game makes it more interesting to players. I was able to make the game go faster as it progressed, therefore making avoiding the obstacles much harder. I also got feedback from a classmate that some of the obstacles spawned in positions that made it impossible for the player to survive, which wasn't fair to them. I was able to change the frequency of the obstacle spawns so that the player wasn't put in an impossible situation.

3. Architecture of My Game

The GamePanel is the most important part of the game because it has the timers and methods that control the FPS, spawning, and changes between the game states. The ObjectManager is also an important part of the game because it controls and interacts with all of the objects in the game: the car, the coins, and all the obstacles. Each object has its own class with code that draws it the way it should look, but its x, y, width, height, speed, and lane variables are all held in the GameObject class. Overall, the GamePanel and the ObjectManager are the classes controlling everything.

4. Technical Implementation

One aspect of the game is the scrolling background. I knew that I'd have to create an image that would repeat when it hits the end of the image, so I first created a seamless racetrack image that could be put as the background for my game. After that I had to go about loading the BufferedImage as the background and making sure it lined up with the width and height of the frame. I created a method that incremented the y values of the corners of the image by a certain "scrollSpeed" so it would move up and scroll through the entire image. I then wrote an if statement to check if it had reached the bottom of the image so I could then reset it back to the top. This way, it looks like the racetrack is a continuous image that is moving which is more interesting than a static image for the background.

5. Most Challenging Part

Probably the most complicated part of the game that I was proud to pull off was controlling the obstacles and coins. It was really tricky to get the coins and the obstacles to spawn in an individual lane without overlapping or forming a barrier that made it impossible for the user. I had to use a lot of if statements to make sure that they didn't spawn in the same lane and that they still left a clear space for the car. I also had to start all the obstacles off at a negative y value because when they switched to their designated lane they seemed to overlap with each other. At first, the collision boxes didn't seem to be working either because the code would not run when it looked like the car and the obstacles collided. It turned out that the collision boxes were not getting updated with the movement of the objects, so I had to make sure they got updated frequently. There were a lot of factors that made the obstacles and coins not work but eventually I was able to work through all of them.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

I would like to change the patterns of the obstacle spawning a little more or do something to make the obstacles more challenging to avoid instead of simply changing the speed. If I had the time I would also like to add levels to the game so it can have one specific goal, instead of the simple goal of collecting as many coins as possible. I would attempt to fix the scrolling background as well, because despite the fact that it's seamless, it still looks like it lags a little bit when it reaches the end. It's not a huge problem but it would make the game a little bit smoother.
